<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Gnarl wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I finaly got to experience the 4 man rule and now I understand why folks hate Enchanters so much in GoD. Forcing us into a role of having not only that much power and requiring that half your group sit back and watch while you single handedly take down mobs is simply ludicrous. For those that don't understand this, the 4 man rule is that when charming, if you have a 4th person on the aggro table the aggro goes haywire. Thus, a puller brings in a mob, a charmer attacks with the charmed pet, and a healer keeps the pet(s) alive. If anyone else joins in the fray, the critter being attacked will lose interest in killing the pet that is taking it down, and go after the charmer, then wipe the group. This means that everything works fine so long as group members 4, 5, and 6 sit and watch OR if the charmer kits. How anyone could think that this was a viable solution, I'm not sure. It really doesn't stop folks from using charm, it just modifies their behavior and causes half your group to feel useless. This 'rule' needs to be stricken, or modified so that the other members in the group can play an active role while the group is still more efficient. ANY case where ANY of the members of a group are most efficient while sitting on their thumbs is NOT acceptable. All members of a group should feel usefull and helpful. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I usually did Tipt/Vxed using a tank and a charmed pet for pure DPS.  Pure-DPS charmed pets are so much safer than tanking charmed pets it isn't funny.
<br />

<br />
This also let the entire group participate and got rid of unstable aggro problems.
<br />

<br />
I have also done Tipt/Vxed's using the double-pet technique (2 charmed hasted geared pets, snarer, cleric) with all healing occurring between fights.  In this case, the entire group is along for the ride: on the other hand, the entire group tends to help with active crowd control.  My first Tipt was like this, 2 ENC and a 2-boxed cleric+ranger.
<br />

<br />
Not using a tactic like this means that a charm break on a summoning mob is pretty disasterous.  And given the length of Tipt/Vxed, it wasn't worth the risk.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Londo wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Enchanters don't share pet aggro. If you get aggro when a 5th object is added onto the mob's hatelist its because you were above the rest of the group for aggro. Adding a 5th object to the hatelist is exactly the same as when people accidentally bda a tank. The tank drops to the bottom of the hatelist and the second person ends up tanking.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I believe a percentage of your pet's aggro is moved to the controller, but I'm not certain.  In any case, it isn't shared aggro.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Gnarl wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">That said, I was thinking of Tipt/Vxed missions where it requires one heckuva tank to stand up to a mob as you've described... thus, having the tank in the mix to hold aggro so the whole group can participate ends up being a liability, not an advantage. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I did Tipt/Vxed's with a 8 k L 65 tank.  Is that one hell of a tank?  We did have a bard pulling.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Gnarl wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In any case, any coding that puts the players in a position where it's more efficient to go AFK and read a book while one or three key individuals carries the day is not good coding. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I agree.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Unmei wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Yakk wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I like the idea of varied mezzes.  I don't like the idea of having the -MR modifier change: it matters far far too much.
<br />

<br />
Here are a bunch of mezzes that don't vary in their -MR, but are quite different:
<br />

<br />
( all of the following with a -10 MR modifier: )
<br />
1.0 casting time, 5.0 recast, 4 tick mez.
<br />
4.0 casting time, 5.0 recast, 15 to 20 tick mez.
<br />
1.5 casting time, 12.0 recast, 1 tick PBAOE mez.
<br />
4.0 casting time, 5.0 recast, 6 tick AoE mez.
<br />
2.5 casting time, 2.3 recast, 9 tick mez.
<br />
0.5 casting time. 10.0 recast, 9 tick mez with a 5000 point 100% spell/melee damage absorbtion effect on it.  And a 10,000 point spell+melee damage shield.  ;-)  (ok, ignoring the DS, this is what Stasis should have been -- a mez that takes work to break)
<br />

<br />
One idea for a mez with a different MR modifier would be one with a +10 MR modifier, but debuffs MR by 20 (or a touch more).  This mez would be a long-term lockdown mez, specifically crippled so it can't be used for lockdown safely.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Some good ideas there.  But I would still think that a -40 or so resist mod mez, with a sufficently high mana cost and recast would be a valuable tool.  What I'm looking at is something like a shorter, less effective rapture.  Rapture was a broken spell, but I think that a spell that can be fired off at the beginning of a big pull, at high mana cost, that gives a good chance of taking one mob out of the picture for 20 or 30 seconds would be a very valuable item.  You wouldn't want to hold anything down with it. Heck, if you want, make the recast long enough that you -can't- hold anything down with it (4 tic duration, 30 second recast works.)  but a little extra edge for a lot of extra mana is really something that I feel would be valuable.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
First of all, a long recast means that this lockdown mez gets resisted, enchanter gets aggro, and enchanter goes splat.
<br />

<br />
I fear any high-mod spell will be turned into <span style="font-style: italic">the</span> raid-mez.
<br />

<br />
Want a mob to be hard to mez?  Well, if so, the -40 resist mez makes it much easier.  It will require to enchanters to hit their mez keys in order to keep him locked down reliably.  This isn't fun, but the math tends to make it optimal.
<br />

<br />
It happened with Rapture.
<br />

<br />
If all mezzes have the same net resist modifier, it means that it isn't the mob which decides which mez we use -- it is the situation.
<br />

<br />
Maybe you are right, and next time it will be different, and a recast-balanced mez won't result in the ridiculousness of rapture.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
