<span class="postbody">Talismanbts wrote: "Bring back illusion faction 
<br />

<br />
I would LOVE to get Illusions back, because using them as faction adjuster was a big part of the class.......I think Lilly's idea has some merit, but needs a LOT of work. The racial thing is not the way to go (IMO). Factions should be brought back though. It makes no sense to see Werewolf/Boon people sitting in the city whiling away the hours at a loom.  Although I like illusions, I don't think they should be used to address all the shortcomings we have been handed recently. "
<br />

<br />
All the mobs have "see through illusion" right now and have the god-like ability to see your faction without ever having even met you.  This is just un-fair and defeats illusions totally.  Faction should be important but not insumountable.  If there is some specific quest that SOE wants you to have some specific faction to complete without using an illusion then those specific npc's should be given the ability to "see illusion" and not give the quest reward or otherwise operate to advance the quest. For the majority of npc's, I was in neriac just the other day, and I was kos as a de to the green conning guards who were ready to attack me in de illusion.  They have not even seen me in years, how god-like in memory and inconsistant in role-play is that? 
<br />

<br />
The issue is not to make illusions the be all and end all, but to illustrate how flavor could be placed into our class definition to make it more logical and consistant.  I gave examples previously of the generic root spell many classes have being replaced with illusions that would have the same effects but different graphics other than roots coming out of the ground, such as illusionary walls of fire or ice, and based upon those resists.  I gave the example of a fly spell using a griffin illusion. There are many spells that we have that could have the way they work from a role-play perspective replaced by logical illusions.  Yes, we would still do the same things, but we would do them by illusions.  Take the fear spell line that many classes have.  For us, the graphic might be that we change briefly for a few seconds into the highest level mob in the zone and this vision would scare the mob and make him run.  This would not be a real illusion that overwites any of our existing illusions, but would just be a spell graphic that would be visible when you cast it.  When we mez or charm,  perhaps we could get a spell graphic that mimiked the mob we were charming in whatever form it has.  When we cast strangle, why can't we get a graphic of a hand choaking the mob? Have you ever wondered also, why strangle also works on undead who don't breath?  Some things just don't make logical sense.  I want to see illusions worked into our role more, they should be the WAY we do what we do, even if it is the same function and has the same effect as a spell of a different class. Our EFFECTS are due to us using ILLUSIONS, like a druid's effects are from using NATURE, or a necro's effects come from using the dead, even if they all have the same effect of root or fear, the WAY each class does it needs to be defined and spells consistant with that definition need to developed.
<br />

<br />
We need a consistent explanation for our abilities that involves our using  ILLUSIONS to achieve them, and these effects need to be expanded so that our abilities are more adaptable and versitile, as I have previously discussed.  
<br />

<br />
Lillywhite</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
