<br />

<br />
You wrote: "Illusions to cause damage? Nope we have that in . . . Dots and Nukes. Illusions to root? Nope we already have . . . Root. "
<br />

<br />
My purpose in this was to give us an alternative way to do croud control on mobs with incredible mr.  If you can't get a mez to land due to mr, then geting a root to land that is also based on magic resistance brings us back to the same problem, we can't control the mob.  If we had a different way of rooting based on resistances other than magic, we would have alternatives when mez could not land. Shaman have disease based slows, why not give an ench a cold based one where the mob believes an illusion its arms are freezing up?  The spell could be a flat rate 40% slow and immune to partial mitigation, maybe not as good or effective as forlorn deeds ot the shaman slow, but still effecting and less resisted option. For root, I suggested a ring of fire illusion that would be based on the attacking the mob's fire resistance. 
<br />

<br />
This post was for "new ideas".  I had 2 goals.  The first was to give enchanters useful abilities based upon their job description as "masters of illusion and mental manipulation."  Well, we do not have that now.  For all of the ideas above,  I was just trying to give EXAMPLES of how our spells could be better related to this job description from a consistent role play point of view. The second was to solve real problems and issues in new ways while still advancing the first idea.  One EXAMPLE, was combat illusions that are based upon resistances other than magic would be very useful, add flexability, and provide us with alternatives solutions to existing problems in game play. And I have tried to show how these 2 "new ideas" could be merged together in a consistant logical way. 
<br />

